d-only with no Bash, I could not independently execute the 10 expected validation commands (npm run closeout-pack-plan:validate, closeout-pack:validate, npm test, npm run validate, spec:requirements:validate, weighted:validate, fullplan:validate, goal:closeout:validate, rp00:control-plane:validate, git diff --check); I verified the binding, validator logic, tests, live plan/queue, ledger sha, and the contract projection by inspection only. The manifest still shows status:in_progress, production_ready:false, and production_ready_descriptor_verified:false, so no claim is overstated at this point.","recommendation":"Before flipping production_ready and committing, ensure the deterministic closeout pipeline produces command-evidence.json capturing passing results for all 10 validation commands, plus adjudication.md and construction-inspection.json, and that human final approval is recorded prior to any runtime/enterprise-trust opening. Treat this PASS as conditioned on that command-evidence.","post_review_disposition":"Non-blocking. Expected pre-closeout state confirmed against the closed CP00-825 pattern; does not block pack or goal closeout. Surfaced to bound the scope of a read-only review."},{"id":"CP826-REV-02","severity":"P3","title":"production_ready_flag label may read as an assertion while production_ready is false","file":"docs/closeout-packs/cp00-826/manifest.json","line":1542,"details":"production_ready_flag is set to "platform_extensibility_synthetic_fixture_interface_bridge_descriptor_verified" while production_ready:false (line 6) and implementation_summary.production_ready_descriptor_verified:false (line 1561). The adjacent _descriptor_verified:false and top-level production_ready:false make the true state unambiguous, and the *_flag string is a stable per-pack identifier (consistent with the CP820-CP826 bindings in registry.js and the contract current_pack/latest_pack), not an assertion of readiness. A future reader skimming only the flag name could nonetheless misinterpret it as a verified claim.","recommendation":"Optionally clarify (naming or a comment) that production_ready_flag is a descriptor label, not a readiness assertion, and that production_ready / production_ready_descriptor_verified are authoritative. No code or data change required.","post_review_disposition":"Non-blocking readability nit. State is internally disambiguated by production_ready:false and production_ready_descriptor_verified:false."},{"id":"CP826-REV-03","severity":"P3","title":"changed-file-scope.json lists new-session-handoff.md as both untracked implementation file and unrelated preserved file","file":"artifacts/closeout-pack-claude-review/cp00-826/changed-file-scope.json","line":144,"details":"docs/closeout-pack-plan/new-session-handoff.md appears in both untracked_implementation_files (line 144) and unrelated_dirty_files_preserved (line 151), which are semantically opposed categories. This is immaterial to the active pack boundary: the active scope is defined by active_pack_implementation_refs (the 5 modified RP27 files: contracts/platform-extensibility-contract.json, packages/platform/src/registry.js, packages/platform/src/validators.js, packages/platform/test/model.test.js, scripts/validate-rp27-platform-extensibility-contract.mjs) plus active_pack_required_untracked_files (docs/closeout-packs/cp00-826), neither of which includes new-session-handoff.md, and active_untracked_implementation_files_omitted is empty, so no required active file is dropped. scripts/progress-control-room-data.mjs and tools/progress-control-room/index.html are correctly kept out of the active refs and listed as unrelated dirty files.","recommendation":"Optionally tighten the changed-file-scope generator so a preserved/unrelated file is not simultaneously emitted under untracked_implementation_files, to keep provenance auditing unambiguous. No impact on the pack deliverables.","post_review_disposition":"Non-blocking provenance bookkeeping note in the revie